Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Power nap optimization (10-20 minutes)
Full cycle nap design (90 minutes)
Caffeine nap technique (coffee + 20 min nap)
Chronotype-based nap timing
Post-lunch dip management (circadian alertness curve)
Sleep inertia prevention and management
Napping without nighttime sleep disruption
Shift worker nap strategies
Pre-event nap protocols (before late nights or early mornings)
Polyphasic sleep awareness (and why it's usually bad)

Methodologies & Frameworks
Nap Types: Power nap (15-20 min), Disco nap (pre-event 90 min), Coffee nap (caffeine + 20 min), Full cycle (90 min)
Timing Science: Post-lunch dip (1-3 PM), Circadian alertness curve, Adenosine clearance
Duration Science: <20 min = Stage 1-2 (alertness boost), 20-60 min = danger zone (deep sleep entry, grogginess), 90 min = full cycle (REM + deep)
Sleep Inertia: Caused by waking from deep sleep, avoided by keeping naps under 20 min or exactly 90 min
Cutoff Rules: No naps after 3 PM (general), adjust for bedtime — minimum 6-7 hours before intended sleep

Reference Documentation
1. Nap Duration Guide
Comprehensive guide covering:
- 10-minute nap: Quick alertness boost, no inertia risk
- 20-minute nap: Optimal power nap, cognitive restoration
- 30-minute nap: Danger zone — entering deep sleep, grogginess likely
- 60-minute nap: Deep sleep included, memory benefits but inertia risk
- 90-minute nap: Full sleep cycle, creativity and complex learning benefits

2. Nap Timing by Chronotype
Complete timing library:
- Early birds (Lions): Ideal nap window 12:00-1:30 PM
- Regular (Bears): Ideal nap window 1:00-2:30 PM
- Night owls (Wolves): Ideal nap window 2:00-3:30 PM
- Always before the 3 PM cutoff for nighttime sleep protection

3. Special Situations
Technical reference with:
- Pre-event nap: 90 min in afternoon before a late night
- Shift work naps: Prophylactic napping before night shifts
- Jet lag naps: Strategic napping for time zone adjustment
- Parent naps: "Sleep when baby sleeps" optimization
- Student naps: Pre-exam memory consolidation naps

Nap Patterns
Pattern 1: The Power Nap (20 Minutes)
Quick midday recharge:
- Timing: 1:00-2:30 PM (align with post-lunch dip)
- Set alarm for exactly 20 minutes
- Find a quiet, dim spot (even car or desk with head rest)
- Close eyes — even without falling fully asleep, benefits occur
- Post-nap: Brief walk or splash cold water on face
- Benefit: +34% alertness improvement (NASA study)

Pattern 2: The Coffee Nap (25 Minutes)
Caffeine + nap synergy:
- Drink coffee or espresso quickly (don't sip slowly)
- Immediately lie down and nap for 20 minutes
- Caffeine takes ~20 minutes to kick in — you wake as it activates
- Double boost: sleep clears adenosine + caffeine blocks adenosine receptors
- Best for: afternoon slumps when you need peak performance after

Pattern 3: The Full Cycle Nap (90 Minutes)
Complete sleep cycle for deep restoration:
- Only on days with significant sleep debt or pre-event preparation
- Must be early enough (before 2 PM) to protect nighttime sleep
- Set alarm for 90 minutes exactly
- Expect vivid dreams (REM included in this duration)
- Allow 15 minutes post-nap for full awakening
- Warning: Regular 90-min naps may indicate insufficient nighttime sleep

Best Practices
Execution
- 20 minutes is the sweet spot — set an alarm, never "see how you feel"
- Even resting with eyes closed without sleep provides 50% of nap benefits
- Consistency helps: same time, same place trains nap ability
- Dim light + cool temperature + quiet = faster nap onset
- Post-nap grogginess lasting >15 min means the nap was too long

Rules
- Never nap within 6-7 hours of bedtime — it steals sleep pressure
- Naps SUPPLEMENT nighttime sleep, they don't REPLACE it
- If you need naps every single day, investigate nighttime sleep quality
- The "I can't nap" belief is usually wrong — it's a trainable skill
- Don't nap to avoid dealing with poor nighttime sleep habits

Warning Signs
- Needing naps daily despite 7-8 hours of nighttime sleep → investigate sleep quality
- Napping 3+ hours regularly → potential sign of depression or medical condition
- Naps completely replacing nighttime sleep → unsustainable, address root cause
- Sleep inertia lasting 30+ minutes → nap duration or timing needs adjustment

